===Expeditions with all parties presumed lost=== {| class="sortable wikitable" |- ! style="width:21%;"| Name ! style="width:15%;"| Leader ! style="width:7%;"| Year lost ! style="width:10%;"| Region ! style="width:55%;"| Comments |- valign="top" | '''[[Vandino and Ugolino Vivaldi|Vivaldi expedition]]''' | [[Ugolino Vivaldi|Vandino and Ugolino Vivaldi]] | 1291 | [[Morocco]] (North Africa) | {{flagicon|Republic of Genoa}} Genoese exploration voyage to find a sea route to India. It was one of the first recorded voyages to sail from the Mediterranean into the Atlantic Ocean since the [[fall of the Roman Empire]] in the 5th century AD, and predated attempts by [[Christopher Columbus]] and [[Vasco da Gama]] by two centuries. |- valign="top" | '''[[Abu Bakr II#Trans-Atlantic travel|Abubakari expedition]]''' | [[Abu Bakr II|Abubakari II]] | 1311 | [[Atlantic Ocean]] | {{flagicon|Mali}} [[Mansa (title)|Mansa]] of the [[Mali Empire]] who abdicated his throne in order to explore "the limits of the ocean". |- valign="top" | '''Ferrer Expedition''' | [[Jaume Ferrer]] | 1346 | [[Cape Bojador]] (Western Sahara) | [[File:Armoiries Majorque.svg|20px]] Majorcan expedition to locate a fabled "river of gold" somewhere on the African continent. |- valign="top" | '''[[John Cabot#Final voyage|Cabot's final expedition]]''' | [[John Cabot]] | 1499 | [[Atlantic Ocean]] | {{flagicon|England}} English expedition to explore [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] and [[eastern Canada]]. |- valign="top" | '''Corte-Real expedition''' | [[Gaspar Corte-Real]] | 1501 | [[Labrador]] (Canada) | {{flagicon|POR}} Portuguese expedition to discover the [[Northwest Passage]]. Part of the expedition, captained by Gaspar's brother [[Miguel Corte-Real]], were sent back to Portugal and are the only known survivors from this expedition. |- valign="top" | '''Corte-Real rescue expedition''' | [[Miguel Corte-Real]] | 1502 | [[Atlantic Ocean]] | {{flagicon|POR}} Portuguese rescue mission to search for lost explorer [[Gaspar Corte-Real]]. |- valign="top" | '''[[James Knight (explorer)#The Northwest Passage expedition|Knight expedition]]''' | [[James Knight (explorer)|James Knight]] | 1721 | [[Marble Island]] (Canadian Arctic) | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to discover the [[Northwest Passage]]. |- valign="top" | '''[[Jean-FranÃ§ois de Galaup, comte de LapÃ©rouse#Scientific expedition - around the world|LapÃ©rouse expedition]]''' | [[Jean-FranÃ§ois de Galaup, comte de LapÃ©rouse]] | 1788 | [[Victoria Strait]] (Oceana) | {{flagicon|FRA}} French expedition which vanished while attempting to sail around the world. |- valign="top" | '''[[Daniel Houghton#Death|Houghton expedition]]''' | [[Daniel Houghton]] | 1791 | [[Sahara]] (North Africa) | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to explore the [[Gambia River]] and the hinterland of Africa's west coast. |- valign="top" | '''[[George Bass#Final voyage|Bass expedition]]''' | [[George Bass]] | 1803 | Pacific Ocean | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to Tahiti, and possibly to the Spanish colony of Chile, before returning to the Sydney colony. |- valign="top" | '''[[Franklin's lost expedition]]''' | [[John Franklin]] | 1845 | [[Victoria Strait]] (Canadian Arctic) | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to traverse the last unnavigated section of the [[Northwest Passage]]. |- valign="top" | '''[[Ludwig Leichhardt#Disappearance|Leichhardt expedition]]''' | [[Ludwig Leichhardt]] | 1848 | McPherson's Station, Coogoon (Western Australia) | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to explore northern and central Australia. |- valign="top" | '''[[Eduard Vogel#Death|Vogel expedition]]''' | [[Eduard Vogel]] | 1856 | [[OuaddaÃ¯ Prefecture|Wadai]] (Central Africa) | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to find a trade route to Asia that bypassed the Middle East. He was initially a party member of the [[Heinrich Barth|Barth expedition]] but eventually left to go exploring on his own and disappeared a year later. In a visit to Wadai in 1873, Gustav Nachtigal was told that the Sultan of Wadai had ordered Vogel's death. |- valign="top" | '''[[Terra Nova Expedition|''Terra Nova'' expedition]]''' | [[Robert Falcon Scott]] | 1913 | [[Antarctica]] | {{flagicon|UK}} British expedition to become the first to reach the geographical [[South Pole]]. |- valign="top" | '''Rusanov expedition''' | [[Vladimir Rusanov]] | 1913 | [[Kara Sea]] (Arctic) | {{flagicon|RUS}} Russian naval expedition to the Arctic to find the [[Northern Sea Route]]. |- valign="top" | '''[[Percy Fawcett#Final expedition|Fawcett expedition]]''' | [[Percy Fawcett]] | 1925 | [[Dead Horse Camp]] (Brazil) | {{flagicon|UK}} British archaeological expedition to the Amazon to locate the "[[Lost City of Z]]". |- valign="top" | '''[[Richard Halliburton#Sea Dragon Expedition|''Sea Dragon'' expedition]]''' | [[Richard Halliburton]] | 1939 | near [[Midway Island]] (Pacific Ocean) | {{flagicon|US}} American expedition attempting to sail a [[Chinese junk]] across the Pacific Ocean from Hong Kong to San Francisco for the [[Golden Gate International Exposition]]. |}
===Expeditions with one or more surviving members=== {| class="sortable wikitable" |- ! style="width:21%;"| Name ! style="width:7%;"| Leader ! style="width:7%;"| Year lost ! style="width:10%;"| Region ! style="width:55%;"| Comments |- valign="top" | '''[[TiburÃ³n Island Tragedy|Grindell expedition]]''' | Thomas F. Grindell | 1905 | [[Sonoran Desert]] ([[TiburÃ³n Island]]) | {{flagicon|US}} American gold prospecting expedition that went missing while exploring TiburÃ³n Island. They were widely believed to have been killed by [[Seri people|Seri]] or [[Yaqui|Yaqui natives]]. However, the remains of Thomas Grindell were discovered by another group of explorers a year later. Of the five-man party, there were only two known survivors: Jack Hoffman and [[Tohono O'odham|Papago]] guide Dolores Valenzuela. |- valign="top" | '''[[Brusilov expedition]]''' | [[Georgy Brusilov]] | 1913 | [[Kara Sea]] (Arctic) | {{flagicon|RUS}} Russian naval expedition to the Arctic to find the [[Northern Sea Route]]. There were only two known survivors: [[Valerian Albanov]] and [[Alexander Konrad]]. |}
